<div class="mt-8">
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    So let's just start with the obvious question — what is an online pH calculator? It's a tool that works out how acidic or basic a solution is. That's it. You give it one input — a hydrogen ion concentration, a hydroxide concentration, or a pH value you've already got written down somewhere — and it returns all four values at once: pH, pOH, [H+], and [OH-]. Now, why does something like this need to exist? Honestly, because pH calculations come up in so many different contexts, and doing the logarithm math from scratch every single time is just tedious. It's not hard exactly, it's just annoying. Chemistry assignments, water treatment verification, reef tank adjustments, homebrewing, soil work, pharmaceutical lab calculations — it keeps showing up. This calculator handles four different modes: from [H+], from a known pH, from [OH-], and from mixing two solutions together. And this is worth saying clearly before anything else — every result shows the actual formula that produced the number, not just the number itself. That's important. A bare answer with no working shown is pretty useless if you're trying to understand what's happening or figure out why something doesn't look right.
  </p>
</div>
<div class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">What is pH?</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    pH stands for "potential of hydrogen." It tells you how many hydrogen ions — H⁺ — are dissolved in a solution at any given moment. That count determines whether the solution is acidic, neutral, or basic. The scale itself runs from 0 to 14 under normal conditions — here's the pH scale explained:
  </p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm text-left border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
      <thead class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-800 font-semibold">
        <tr>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 border-b border-slate-200">pH Range</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 border-b border-slate-200">Classification</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 border-b border-slate-200">Common Examples</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-slate-600">
        <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">0–3</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Strongly Acidic</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Battery acid, gastric acid</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-slate-100 bg-slate-50">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">4–6</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Mildly Acidic</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Coffee, rainwater, tomato juice</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">7</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Neutral</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Pure water</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-slate-100 bg-slate-50">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">8–10</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Mildly Basic</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Seawater, baking soda solution</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">11–14</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Strongly Basic</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Bleach, drain cleaner</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <img
    src="/images/ph-scale-chart.webp"
    alt="pH scale chart showing acidic, neutral, and basic ranges from 0 to 14"
    class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 my-6"
    loading="lazy"
    width="1200"
    height="400"
  />

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Here's the thing that actually catches people off guard when they first genuinely sit with this. That scale is not linear. Not even close. It's logarithmic, which sounds like a footnote, but it completely rewires how you have to think about these numbers. pH 5 isn't slightly worse than pH 6. It's ten times more acidic. pH 4 is a hundred times more acidic than pH 6. A hundred times. So when a reef hobbyist is visibly stressed about their tank dropping from 8.2 to 7.9 overnight — they're not overreacting. That drop looks tiny written out. In actual chemical terms, it absolutely is not.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    And here's a fun historical footnote that most people don't know. All of this came out of a brewery. In 1909, a Danish chemist named Søren Peder Lauritz Sørensen was working at the Carlsberg Laboratory — yes, that Carlsberg, the one that makes beer — and he was trying to work out how hydrogen ion concentration was affecting enzyme activity during fermentation. He needed a better way to write very small numbers and developed the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/pH" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">logarithmic scale we still use today</a>. Over a hundred years later, and nothing's replaced it. The "p" comes from the German word <em>Potenz</em>, meaning power — as in powers of ten. Every pH value has a mathematical exponent buried inside it.
  </p>
</div>
<div class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">The pH Formula — How pH Gets Calculated</h2>
  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    One equation is doing almost all of the work here:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    pH = −log₁₀[H⁺]
  </div>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    The [H⁺] is the hydrogen ion concentration in mol/L. Taking the negative log flips the relationship — higher ion concentration pushes pH down toward acidic, lower ion concentration pushes pH up toward basic. Once that backwards relationship properly clicks — like actually makes sense rather than just being a rule you memorize — reading a pH scale starts to feel natural rather than backwards.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Going the other way — figuring out [H⁺] from a pH you already have:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    [H⁺] = 10⁻ᵖᴴ
  </div>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    For working with hydroxide ions:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    pOH = −log₁₀[OH⁻]
  </div>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    And the equation that connects both sides at 25°C:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-slate-100 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-slate-800 text-sm my-6">
    pH + pOH = 14
  </div>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    That isn't just a rule somebody put in a chemistry textbook because it seemed convenient. It comes directly from how water behaves at that temperature. In pure water at 25°C, [H⁺] multiplied by [OH⁻] always equals 1×10⁻¹⁴ — that constant is called Kw, the <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/chemistry/ion-product-of-water" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-[#1D9E75] hover:text-[#168561] underline font-medium">ion product of water</a>. Take the negative log of both sides of that expression, and pH + pOH = 14 just falls straight out. Nobody invented that relationship. Water did.
  </p>

  <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
    Quick reference table for which formula to reach for depending on what's already known:
  </p>

  <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm text-left border border-slate-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
      <thead class="bg-slate-100 text-slate-800 font-semibold">
        <tr>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 border-b border-slate-200">Known Value</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-3 border-b border-slate-200">How to Find pH</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-slate-600">
        <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">[H⁺] concentration</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">pH = −log[H⁺]</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-slate-100 bg-slate-50">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">[OH⁻] concentration</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">pOH = −log[OH⁻], then pH = 14 − pOH</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">pH directly</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Already have it — work everything else from it</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Mixed solutions</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Mole balance across the full combined volume</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="mt-8">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-10 mb-4">How to Use This pH Calculator</h2>

  <img
    src="/images/ph-calculator-modes.webp"
    alt="Diagram showing four pH calculator input modes: from H+, from pH, from OH-, and mix solutions"
    class="w-full rounded-lg border border-slate-200 my-6"
